r poise of\ncharacter by bad blood In fact, it\nis a question whether the great majority\nof people do not ruin their\nlives and mar their happiness by\nlack of self-control. How few people\nwo meet in life who have that\nexquisite poise whioh is characteristic\nof the finished character. Ex.\nOne way Colonist rates on salo\nMarch 1st to April 30th at the following\nvery low rates: To points in\nAlberta, 40.65; Artrona, $39; British\nColumbia, 140. 65; California,\n$39; Colorado, $39; Idaho, $40.65;\nMexico, $49; Montana, $40.65; No-J\nvada, $39; New Mexico, $39; Oregon.\n$40.65; Utah; $40.65; Washington,\n$40.65; Wyoming, $40.65.\nFor particular! call on agent I. O.\nR. 11., Marion, Ky.\nj\nL ,7- T T\nT t VI\" 'T.ll I HU\nij ni i nmwnnpriY n ii i wmifcfc iiHmiP\nftM\nBig Crop of Bargains for You\nOurs Are \"Dead Low.\"\nIf You Don't Need Them It Will Pay You to Buy Them\nand Keep them Until You Do.\nWE WANT TO SELL THEM\nand our prices will do it.\nGood Goods at Shoddy Goods Prices!\nTHIS CONCERNS\nWinter Suits, Overcoats, Pants, Shoes\nand Wool Goods.\nWMimmmmmSmMikWm m\nStyle, Quality and Price in\nSpring Merchandise\nNew Wool Dress Goods\nLinens\nSheer Linens\nPersian Lawns\nIndia Linons\nBatistes, Linen Lowns\nDainty Laces, Embroideries\nand Waist Goods.\nA Great Stock to Select From.\nYANDELL-GUGENHEIM COMPANY\nXXSSSSKSKl50Cs.rrCi!jT5ii( ut\nK BIBLE GLASS S\nit\nREV. J, F. PRICE, EDITOR k\nfcjf kjs?ljoc: KKTtf.s.uxg.tfKrrtf8cx.\nHealing of the Man Horn Blind.\nJohn\nTOPICS FOR STUDY.\n1. The woman taken in adultery.\no Christ the light of the werld.\n3. The discussion between Christ\nand the Pharisees.\n4. Healing the blind man.\n5. The pool of Siloam.\n6. The benefit of experience.\n7. Study the blind man's character\nfor fairness and common sense.\nS. Point out the sophistry in the\nobjections raised by the pharisecs.\n9. Show how that it is far more\nthan a figure of speech to say that\nChrist is the light of the world.\n10. Give all the cases of bliidness\nhealed by Christ.\nSEARCH QUESTIONS.\n1. When Jesus attended the\nfeasts, where did ho usually make\nhis home?\n2. How did the Pharisees try to\nentrap him? John 8; 3, 5.\n3. How did he confute them?\n4. What testimony did Jesus\nChris give to himself?\n5. Who else bore testimony to\nChrist.\nWhat contrast did ho make\nbetween Himself and the Pharisees.\n7. In what way did he speak to\nthem of his crucifixion?\n8. What freedom does Christ give\nus?\n9. W hat contrast did he make between\nhis Father and theirs?\n10. Of what did they accuse\nChrst?\n11. What saying of his confused\nthem?\n12. Who is presented at the opening\nof chapter IX?\n13. What effect had the talk about\nthe bread of lifo on Christ's hearers?\n14. To what province did Jesus\nconfine his ministry for a time?\n15. Where did the miracles of the\nlesson occur?\n16. What can you say about the\npool of Siloam? Sec Nch. 3:15; Isa.\n8:6.\n17. What did Jesus do to the\nblind man?\n18 What did he tell him to do?\n19. What coincidence between the\nmanner of the miracle and the name\nof the pool docs the evangelist point\nout?\n20. Compare their miracle, for\nwith the one in chapter\nfive.\n21. Why does its aim differ from\nthat of other miracles?\n22. What confession of faith did\nJesus on finding the man draw from\nhim?\n23. What did Jesus defino as his\nmission in tho world?\n24. What mado it diffltilt for the\nJews to credit Christ's testimony?\n25. How did his parents evade an\nanswer, and why?\n26. In the dialogue, vs. 26-33\nwho get the best of it?\n27. What is the final argument of\nthe Jews?\n2S. Give the seven miracles of\nmercy wrought on the Sabbath.\n29. What discourse did Jesus base\nupon the miracles? See chapter X.\n30. Why did the disciples believe\nthat suffering was the result of sin?\nSec Ex., 20:5; Acts 28:1.\n31. To what extent is this true,\nand to what extent is it an errors?\n32. Is there any recorded case of\nblindness healed in tho Old Testament?\n33. Which arc the most valuable\nchristian evidence, facts or arguments?\n34. To what facts may we still appeal\nto prove that Christ is divine?\n35. Is any mere argument valid\nagainst the facts?\n36. Who are are Christ's most ef\nfective witnesses?\n37. Is any testimony sufficient to\nconvince one who docs not want to\nsee?\nPool of Siloam.\nThis pool was at the foot of the\nhill south of tho temple area, in the\nvalley called Tyropeon, which runs\nthrough the midst of Jerusalem cast\nof the temple, and near the junction\nof the valley with that of the Ked-son.\nThe pool was fed by a tunnel\n1700 ft. long from the fountain of\nthe Virgin, the only real spriug near\nJerusalem. The flow into this\nspring ig intermittent, being of the\nnature of a siphon from the fountain\nof the Virgin to the pool of Siloam\nconveys more water than flows into\nthe fountain for the same length of\ntime. This fissure rises several feet\nhigher than its opening itothe fountain.\nWhen the water begins to\nflow, it continues until it exhausts\nthe water into the fountain down to\nthe opening of the siphon. Then\nit ceases to flow until the water in\nfountain rises to the highest part of\ntho siphon. The frequency of tho\nintervals occur in the proportion to\nthe amount of rain. In rainy weath\ner it flows from three to five times a\nday, in summer about twice a day,\nand in autumn about once ft day. In\nthe time of Christ there was an arcade\ntwelve feet wide and roofed at\nthe height of twenty two feet and all\nthe pool.\nThe seven miracles of mercy\nwrought on the Sabbath day were:\nthe withered hand, the demoniac at\nCapernaum, Peter's wife's mothor,\nwoman bowed down eightcon years,\nman with tho leprosy, impotcut man\nman at Bcthesda, man born blind.\nLook them up.\nShade Trees For Sale.\nA few hundred nice, soft maplo\ntrees for sale. Quiok growth. Ten.\nand Twenty cents each.\nW. D. Haynis.\nGeneral Business Outlook.\nThe attitude of manufacturers and\nmerchants all along the line is ono\nof reasonable conservatism, and while\ncaution and economy are strikingly\nmanifest, there is a hopeful feeling\nthat tho country will gradually recover\nfrom the recent financial shock.\nThe 50,000,000 sale of New York\nCity bonds was an unqualified suc\ncess, aud the number and aggregate\nvalue of the bids was naturally regarded\nas encouraging. There were\nreasons for regarding these issues\nwith special favor, as these bonds are\navailable for trustees and saving\nbanks, and the credit of the city is\nfirst rate. Hut as regards other investments\ngreat discrimination is\nexercised, and the uncertainties existing\nover the political and business\noutlook tends to a lack of confidence.\nPolitical developments are responsible\nfor much of the pessimistic sentiment\nprevailing, and the swinging\nof tht \"big stick\" is keeping business\ninterests guessing. If we were\nliving under an absolute monarchy\nwe might be reconciled to the \"one\nman rule\" form of government, but\nas this great country is not willing\nto come under the yoke of the new\ninnovation on American soil, we\nsuppose we must look upon the\nmethod of wordy reform as a passing\ncpisrdc in our national history.\nThe worst of it all is that while the\ncataclysm lasts neither the capitalist,\nartisan or laborer is getting a\nfair chance for the excrciso of his\nlegitimate aspirations, and many of\nthe latter have to endure the hardship\nof non-employment. Individual\ninitiative in enterprise has been repressed\non account of recent governmental\ntendencies, and nationrl leaders\nof both great parties, in too\nmany cases, seem to have becomo\nimbued with the idea that the country\ncan be lectured into tho adoption\nof untried and erratic policies which\nwould givo a select set of men a\nconcentration of inquisitorial power\nI over railroads and business whioh no\n'free people ought to rashly intrust\nto any body of men. Business conditions\nof today call loudly for rest\nfrom unconstitutional dictation and\ninterference beyond that which is\nrecognized by statutory enactment\nand legal usage. Aud above all,\ntho country would welcome the opportunity\nto attend to the functions\nof business and industry without any\nmore scolding. Gossip.\nMarch The Fourth Is Ash Wednesday.\nMarch 4, in the church calendar,\nis Ash Wednesday, the beginning of\nLent. Easter, the ond of Lent, falls\non April 19. Lent is a fast of forty\ndays, observed as commemorative of\ntho fast of Christ. The simple process\nof counting the days on tho\ncalender from March 4 to April 19,\nwill demonstrate the fact that this\nyear Lent is not a fast of forty days,\nbut of forty seven day3.\nThe intracies of tin- o.tlrn'ier are\ntoo profound for full explanation in\nshort space, and it l.s sutficieut to accept\na forty-seven day lent as a fact.\nHowever, the observance of Lent will\nnot properly begin until next Sunday\nalthough March fourth will be observed\nas Ash Wednesday. -Henderson\nJournal.\nTho Lenten season began yesterday\nwhich was Ash Wednesday. It\nis a period of six weeks proceeding\nthe anniversary of tho Saviour's\ndeath, and is set apart as a special\nseason of fasting, ponitence aud\nprayer. It is called Lent, from the\nSaxon word Lent, which moans\nSpring.\nBecause there ars six Sundays in\nLent, and as all Sundays arc feast\ndays, kept in honor of tho Resurrection,\nthey aro taken out, and to make\nup for those six days arc added at\nthe beginning of the season. --Henderson\nGleaner.\nHis Relations With His Father.\nDombcy and son striko a very natural\nchord. John Smith and Son,\nand even John Smith's Son's Sons,\nfloat through parental castles in\nSpain It will be a proud moment\nfor the father when the hopes of a\nscore of years aro rcalizol. The con,\nhowever, may have a quite ditlercut\nambition, may have altogether\nresolutions. Somo dormant\nstrain in the blood has awakened,\nand a gift bequeathed from a forgot\nten ancestor suddenly asserts its\nclaim. Iho boy is an artist, or a\npoet. He longs to paint pictures.\nor to write stories, to weave melodies\nat the keyboard; ho sees visions\nand dreams dreams. To force such\na nature when its demands aro imperious\ninto any groove excopt the\none tho Creator has intonded for it\nis tu uii viuiuucu tu i ne law oi me\nhighest right, is to set a thoroughbred\nto tiic work of an army mule.\nWhen the decision of a lifetime is\nto be made, and the youth is\nhonest to make it with clear\njudgment, his nearest and dearest\nshould keep their hands oil.\nWe live in an ago of great commercial\ngreed, of magnificent material\nsuccess. To many an American\nmoney is the greatest thing in the\nworld. Its golden gleam dazzles his\neyes. Its tremendous power beckons\nhim as onco men wcro beckoned by\nglory or by fame. Tho luxuries\nbrings, the opportunities it makes\npossible, aro imtnensoly attractive\nWhenever and whorcver tho young\nAmerican is found so strong, ho\npoised and so that he\nknows what ho wants, and docs not\nsupremely want money, that man's\npath should be mado straight before\nhim, that he may reach his goal.\nEx.\nBetween a full moon and a full\nman thcro is a distance of sovoral\n'thousand miles.\nrlu\nfB\nm\nw :A\nVjt\nIn n Utile While.\nOn the hillsides lambs will gambol,\nIn a little while,\nDown tho lanes tho cows will amble\nIn a little while;\nFragrant blossoms will be Kwaying\nIn tho gentle brooic,\nLovors will go forth a-Maying\nFull of contacies,\nIn a little while.\nBumble boos will gladly bumble\nIn a little while,\nInto pitchers flio will tumble,\nIn a little while,\nPassing people will be hearing\nGolfers crying \"fore!\"\nWall street will be busy shearing\nTrusty lambs once more,\nIn a little while.\nAll tho woods will ring with gladness\nIn a little while,\nPeople will forget their nadnoss\nIn a little while;\nDoves will be serenely cooing,\nKites will cleave tho air;\nMaddened mobs will bo pursuing\nUmpires horc and there,\nIn a little while.\nChicago\nFor Sale.\nAt my farm, one-half mile West\nof Baker school house tho following:\nHousehold and kitchen furniture,\nono wagon, one buggy and harness,\nono mower, one rake, corn drill aud\nother implements, also two mares,\none colt, cow, calf, five sows, twelve\nshoals, a lot of shcop, hay aud com.\nTerms made known on day of salo.\nDate, March 10th. Kvoryonu\nJ. W. Simpson.\nTo Hen\nA suite of rooms, (3) over the now\nrestaurant in Pierce building. Will\nrent all together or singly.\nJ. P. PlKIK'K,\nFOUYSKIDNEYCURE\nMakes Kidneys and Uladder Rlgbt\nArc You Next\nTo rceoive eye comfort and\ntion hero? If you havo tho slightoH\nsort of eye troubles you will never\n...ii: I..\nviuniijK on us. uo use tho\nlUBi muuurii appliances, wo havo tho\nskill and aro positive that wo can\nfurnish eyeglasses and spectacles to\nmeet ovcry possible requirement.\nDr. Abell's Optical Parlors,\nPrinceton, Ky,\nmMli","height":"28752","width":"20832"}}
